title: For Sale:  WWI-WWII Matching No Import Lee-Enfield BSA Rifle
postcontent: Short Magazine Lee-Enfield No.I Mk.III* Rifle; 1917 Birmingham Small Arms(BSA) Production/British Service; .303 BritishRemarkably clean and matching, this non import-marked SMLE was produced by BSA at the height of the First World War. An outstanding representative of this iconic weapon, this rifle was in service in time to have played a part in WWI, and having remained in service until after the Korean conflict(denoted by the Nitro-Proving marks on the barrel), it undoubtedly saw combat in WWII, and possibly Korea. An outstanding, sturdy service rifle, the Lee-Enfield gave the British soldier of the early 20th century, an almost unmatched advantage in terms of sheer volume of firepower. Having the smoothest bolt action ever designed, the Lee-Enfield often gave the enemy the impression that the Tommies of WWI were armed with automatic rifles. Often seen in well-used condition, this rifle is in stark contrast to those normally encountered by the collector. Non-import marked, it would be an excellent acquisition, worthy of the advanced Enfield collection.Condition:Is near excellent-the rifle shows no sign of post-service refinish, and arsenal bluing is better than 90% having only mild fading and high edge wear. Metal surfaces are void of pitting and rust, and all markings are well-struck, legible and correct. Matching serialized components include the receiver, barrel, bolt handle and nose cap/bayonet lug, with the rear sight being a service replacement, the furniture unnumbered, and the magazine having a different number. As stated, no import mark was found. Mechanically flawless, the action is properly fluid and smooth, while the bore is near excellent with strong, well-defined rifling and no rust or pitting.

title: For Sale:   WWI-WWII Matching No Import Lee-Enfield BSA Rifle
postcontent: Short Magazine Lee-Enfield No.I Mk.III* Rifle; 1917 Birmingham Small Arms(BSA) Production/British Service; .303 BritishRemarkably clean and matching, this non import-marked SMLE was produced by BSA at the height of the First World War. An outstanding representative of this iconic weapon, this rifle was in service in time to have played a part in WWI, and having remained in service until after the Korean conflict(denoted by the Nitro-Proving marks on the barrel), it undoubtedly saw combat in WWII, and possibly Korea. An outstanding, sturdy service rifle, the Lee-Enfield gave the British soldier of the early 20th century, an almost unmatched advantage in terms of sheer volume of firepower. Having the smoothest bolt action ever designed, the Lee-Enfield often gave the enemy the impression that the Tommies of WWI were armed with automatic rifles. Often seen in well-used condition, this rifle is in stark contrast to those normally encountered by the collector. Non-import marked, it would be an excellent acquisition, worthy of the advanced Enfield collection.Condition:Is near excellent-the rifle shows no sign of post-service refinish, and arsenal bluing is better than 90% having only mild fading and high edge wear. Metal surfaces are void of pitting and rust, and all markings are well-struck, legible and correct. Matching serialized components include the receiver, barrel, bolt handle and nose cap/bayonet lug, with the rear sight being a service replacement, the furniture unnumbered, and the magazine having a different number. As stated, no import mark was found. Mechanically flawless, the action is properly fluid and smooth, while the bore is near excellent with strong, well-defined rifling and no rust or pitting.
